# SPA fallback — but scoped to the real client-side routes instead of a blanket `/*`.
#
# A blanket `/* /index.html 200` also catches requests for hashed assets that no longer exist (an
# old content hash after a new deploy): it returns index.html (200, text/html) at a .js/.css URL,
# which trips "text/html is not a valid JavaScript MIME type" and — once Cloudflare caches that
# 200 — poisons the URL so the service worker's atomic update fails and users stay stuck on the old
# build. Cloudflare Pages `_redirects` only supports a trailing splat (no `/*.js`), so we can't
# exclude assets by extension; instead we enumerate the app's routes. Anything else (a missing
# asset) falls through to a native 404, which the browser rejects cleanly and can't cache as JS.
#
# Existing static files (assets, ngsw.json, manifest, /legal/*.md, /i18n/**, icons, og-image, …)
# are served directly — Cloudflare serves a matching file in preference to a 200 rewrite.
#
# Keep this in sync with src/app/app.routes.ts when routes are added or removed.
/                /index.html   200
/profile         /index.html   200
/content         /index.html   200
/auth            /index.html   200
/reset-password  /index.html   200
/map             /index.html   200
/dev             /index.html   200
/dev/*           /index.html   200
/legal/*         /index.html   200
/s/*             /index.html   200
/replay/*        /index.html   200
